Time for some reviews:

Review of "Manhunt" by Mountlear

This story is good, if sporting a few flaws.

It's biggest strength is its fast pace and its action scenes. The description of violence is visceral, striking the right balance between fast pace and slowing down to articulate wounds and agony. And the plot's pace is fast, which I imagine is intended seeing the main conflict is a race against time where the two main characters are racing to find a hidden treasure. The main characters, Lever and Darkness are a nice couple, and their contrasts and interactions are cute. I also like it how Lever can hold his own in combat, something that many /hmofa/ authors tend to ignore when the woman is muscle of the relationship. It's a good change.

There are a few flaws though.

The start of the start of the story is very sudden. There's very little establishment of the world, characters, or plot which does do a disservice to the overall narrative. While its good to avoid info-dumping, too little exposition leaves the reader little grounding. Even just some more time to set up Lever and Darkness's relationship and their place is the world make the plot have a lot more impact. Perhaps how they met, or a bit more on who they are and how they got to the predicament they're in.

There's also a lot more telling rather than showing. One of the most common writing advices repeated is "show don't tell." But this is rather simplistic. Rather a good writer must strike a balance. And while there's definitely show, there's certainly a lot of telling. Again, could add a bit more impact with expanding the plot a bit.

Overall, good medium story.
Anonymous

>Review of "Knight-Cantor" by YellowNoteAnon

This is a sweet story.

The description is good, it flows well, the characterization is great. The highlight especially is the interactions between Eldash and Derrick, their banter and eventual relationship is heartwarming. I also liked how during the combat, Eldash is shown not to be invincible, and can be overwhelmed in the right circumstances, revealing her overconfidence in combat. Much like a real armored knight, while tough, can be brought down with enough coordination.

I don't have any major flaws I can see, but the narrative isn't really long enough to find any. The only thing I could see is it seems a bit out of character for Davis to immediately turn on his former buddies instead of just running. But that can be easily overlooked.

Overall, good story. After reading their other major work "Bed of Snakes," you can tell what the author's taste in women is like (I'm not complaining).

Fun fact. Despite potatoes appearing in many medieval-based fantasy worlds, they are originally from South America and didn't arrive in Europe until the 16th Century.

On thread #3227 there was a little discussion about a leftover icon in Windows and MS Office files. I did a little bit of research and it turns out it relates to FoxPro, something that I can only assume was a mix of MS Access and Visual Basic before those two took over the market. As it so happens, FoxPro has exchanged owners, ultimately being bought out by Microsoft in 1992, and Microsoft did their usual tactic of embrace, extend and extinguish, as they developed FoxPro up until 2007 when it was discontinued. So all those fox icons that still live somewhere in Windows as well as MS Office were those of FoxPro. Picrel is the full res icon of FoxPro.

tl;dr: in every Windows installation there lies a corpse of a tiny vixen that has fallen victim to Microsoft's predatory monopolistic plays.
